description: From Latin obsolētus (“worn out, gone out of use”), past participle of obsolēscere (“to wear out, fall into disuse, grow old, decay”); see obsolesce.

adjectives.description: obsolete (comparative more obsolete, superlative most obsolete)

entries.meaning: (of words, equipment, etc.) No longer in use; gone into disuse; disused or neglected (often in favour of something newer).
examples: Synonyms: antiquated, deprecated, disused; see also Thesaurus:obsolete

description: From Latin obsolētō (“degrade, soil, sully, stain, defile”).

verbs.description: obsolete (third-person singular simple present obsoletes, present participle obsoleting, simple past and past participle obsoleted)

entries.meaning: (transitive, chiefly US) To cause to become obsolete.
examples: This software component has been obsoleted.
We are in the process of obsoleting this product.
